text.tspan: A refreshing course catalogue for Queen's University students.

flowRoot.flowPara: SOLUS, the new university administration system, while technically providing functions for students to find courses, does so in a manner that is often cumbersome and has poor accessibility. The lack of “back” button support in browsers is an example of this.
The SOLUS listing for CISC 121
The Qcumber listing for CISC 121

Qcumber provides the same information as SOLUS, but has the specific aim of facilitating course browsing. This allows it to be more intuitive, public, linkable, and follow a modern website model that students are used to.

Qcumber, at its core, is composed of two separate processes. Periodically, a web scraper systematically browses SOLUS and parses course listings from its pages, storing them in a database. Upon receiving requests, a Django application then displays that information to website clients.
A conceptual diagram of Qcumber

Feedback from students has been extremely positive, with many offering suggestions for features. The project is also open source, and through this, has acquired two extra contributors. They have been responsible for many improvements to the site.

Many thanks go to Carey Metcalfe and Phil Schleihauf for code contributions and programming sessions, and to Nissi Wei for consultations on function. Thanks also go to Dr. Bob Crawford for moral support and advice, and to Christine P’ng for the logo design.
